# SPIRE.md — Agent Work Instructions

This repo is connected to Spire (prefix: **{{.Prefix}}**). Use Spire for work coordination.

## Roles

| Role | What |
|------|------|
| **Archmage** | Human. Writes specs, reviews, steers. |
| **Wizard** | Per-bead orchestrator. Drives the formula lifecycle. |
| **Apprentice** | Implementer. Writes code in isolated worktree. |
| **Sage** | Reviewer. Returns verdict (approve / request changes). |

## Session lifecycle

```bash
spire up                        # ensure services are running
spire collect                   # check inbox
spire claim <bead-id>           # claim work (atomic: verify → set in_progress)
spire focus <bead-id>           # assemble full context
# ... do the work ...
spire send <agent> "done" --ref <bead-id>   # notify others
```

## Formulas drive the lifecycle

Every bead type maps to a formula that defines the phase pipeline:

| Bead type | Formula | Phases |
|-----------|---------|--------|
| epic | `spire-epic` | design → plan → implement (waves) → review → merge |
| bug | `spire-bugfix` | implement → review → merge |
| task, feature, chore | `spire-agent-work` | implement → review → merge |

## Design beads

Design beads capture exploration and decisions BEFORE filing work items.

```bash
spire design "Auth system overhaul"          # → {{.Prefix}}-xxx
# brainstorm, add comments...
bd update {{.Prefix}}-xxx -s closed          # close when settled
spire file "Auth overhaul" -t epic -p 1      # file the work
bd dep add <epic-id> {{.Prefix}}-xxx --type discovered-from   # link design
```

The wizard validates that epics have a closed `discovered-from` design
bead before entering plan. Use `discovered-from` deps, not `ref:` labels.

## Dependencies — prefer deps over labels

Relationships between beads are expressed as **dependencies**, not labels.
The dependency graph is the source of truth for ordering, provenance,
and cross-references. Labels are for routing (messages) and display only.

### When to use each type

| Type | When | Example |
|------|------|---------|
| `blocks` | B can't start until A closes | `bd dep add spi-auth spi-schema --type blocks` |
| `parent-child` | Subtask under an epic | `bd create "Subtask" -t task --parent spi-epic` |
| `discovered-from` | This work came from that design/exploration | `bd dep add <epic> <design-bead> --type discovered-from` |
| `caused-by` | This alert/bug was caused by that bead's failure | `bd dep add <alert> <source> --type caused-by` |
| `supersedes` | This bead replaces an older one | `bd dep add <new> <old> --type supersedes` |
| `related` | Cross-reference, no ordering | `bd dep add <a> <b> --type related` |
| `validates` | This test/check validates that work | `bd dep add <test> <feature> --type validates` |

### The development workflow is defined by the bead type

The bead's **type** maps to a formula, which defines the phases the
wizard drives. These are the defaults — override them per-bead with a
`formula:<name>` label, or per-tower by dropping a TOML in `.beads/formulas/`:

| Bead type | Default formula | Default phases |
|-----------|----------------|----------------|
| epic | `spire-epic` | design → plan → implement (waves) → review → merge |
| bug | `spire-bugfix` | implement → review → merge |
| task, feature, chore | `spire-agent-work` | implement → review → merge |
| design | (none) | Not a work item. Close when settled, link via `discovered-from`. |

Custom formulas can be created in the workshop (`spire workshop`).
Override a built-in per-bead with a `formula:<name>` label, or per-tower
by placing a TOML in `.beads/formulas/`.

### Common patterns

```bash
# Epic with design: brainstorm → file → link → summon
spire design "New auth system"                              # → {{.Prefix}}-abc
bd comments add {{.Prefix}}-abc "Approach: OAuth2 + MFA..." # capture thinking
bd update {{.Prefix}}-abc -s closed                         # design settled
spire file "Auth overhaul" -t epic -p 1                     # → {{.Prefix}}-def
bd dep add {{.Prefix}}-def {{.Prefix}}-abc --type discovered-from
spire summon 1 --targets {{.Prefix}}-def                    # wizard validates design → plans → implements

# Task that blocks another
spire file "Add user table" -t task -p 1                    # → {{.Prefix}}-111
spire file "Add user API" -t task -p 1                      # → {{.Prefix}}-222
bd dep add {{.Prefix}}-222 {{.Prefix}}-111 --type blocks    # API waits for table

# Replacing old work with new
bd dep add {{.Prefix}}-new {{.Prefix}}-old --type supersedes

# Check what's ready to work (no open blockers)
bd ready --json
```

## Filing work

```bash
spire file "Title" -t task -p 2             # prefix auto-detected from repo
spire file "Title" -t epic -p 1             # epic (auto-syncs to Linear)
spire file "Title" -t bug -p 0              # P0 bug
spire design "Title"                        # design bead (not a work item)
```

**Always set priority** (`-p 0` critical → `-p 4` nice-to-have) and
**always set type** (`-t task|bug|feature|epic|chore`).

## The review invariant

Every bead goes through review after implementation. One rule:
**every path ends with the branch either merged to main or deleted.**

```
sage: approve      → merge → main, delete branch, close bead
sage: reject ×3    → arbiter decides:
  arbiter: merge   → force-merge → main, delete branch, close
  arbiter: split   → merge → main, create child beads, close
  arbiter: discard → delete branch, close as wontfix
  any failure      → label needs-human, alert archmage
```

## Completing work

Close things in order:

1. Close molecule steps — `bd close <step-id>` for each
2. Close the bead — `bd close <bead-id>`
3. Push state — `bd dolt push`
4. Notify — `spire send <agent> "done" --ref <bead-id>`

## Messaging

```bash
spire register <name>                       # register as an agent
spire collect                               # check inbox
spire send <to> "message" --ref <bead-id>   # send a message
spire alert "message" --ref <bead-id> -p 1  # priority alert
```

## Monitoring

```bash
spire board              # interactive TUI (h/j/k/l navigate, t type, s summon, f focus, c claim, L logs)
spire board --json       # machine-readable for agents
spire roster             # work grouped by epic, agent status
spire logs <wizard-name> # tail wizard logs
spire metrics            # agent performance summary
```

## Commit format

```
<type>(<bead-id>): <message>
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `chore`, `docs`, `refactor`, `test`

## Key conventions

- **Claim before working** — prevents double-work
- **Investigate before implementing** — trace the data flow, find the root cause
- **Verify before removing** — grep for usage before deleting code or features
- **Never leave branches hanging** — every branch must be merged or deleted

## DANGER

- **NEVER run `bd init --force`** — wipes entire dolt history. No undo.
- **NEVER run `bd init`** on a directory with an existing `.beads/` database.
